{"title_page": "The Girl Who Died", "text_new": "{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 256\n| serial_name        = The Girl Who Died\n| show               = DW\n| type               = episode\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| doctor             = [[Peter Capaldi]] ([[Twelfth Doctor]])\n| companion          = [[Jenna Coleman]] ([[Clara Oswald]])\n| guests             = \n* [[Maisie Williams]] \u2013 [[Ashildr]]\n* [[David Schofield (actor)|David Schofield]] \u2013 [[Odin]]\n* [[Simon Lipkin]] \u2013 Nollarr\n* Ian Conningham \u2013 Chuckles\n* [[Tom Stourton]] \u2013 Lofty\n* Alastair Parker \u2013 Limpy\n* [[Murray McArthur]] \u2013 Hasten\n* [[Barnaby Kay]] \u2013 Heidi\n| director           = [[Edward Bazalgette|Ed Bazalgette]]\n| writer             = [[Jamie Mathieson]] <br />[[Steven Moffat]]\n| script_editor      = Nick Lambon\n| producer           = Derek Ritchie\n| executive_producer = Steven Moffat <br />Brian Minchin\n| composer           = [[Murray Gold]]\n| series             = [[Doctor Who (series 9)|Series 9]]\n| length             = 46 minutes\n| date               = {{Start date|2015|10|17|df=y}}\n| preceding          = \"[[Before the Flood (Doctor Who)|Before the Flood]]\"\n| following          = \"[[The Woman Who Lived]]\"\n}}\n\"'''The Girl Who Died'''\" is the fifth episode of the [[Doctor Who (series 9)|ninth series]] of the British [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. It was first broadcast on [[BBC One]] on 17 October 2015. It is written by [[Jamie Mathieson]] and [[Steven Moffat]] and directed by [[Edward Bazalgette|Ed Bazalgette]].\n\nIn the episode, the alien [[Time travel in fiction|time traveller]] the [[Twelfth Doctor]] ([[Peter Capaldi]]) and his [[Companion (Doctor Who)|companion]] [[Clara Oswald|Clara]] ([[Jenna Coleman]]) have 24 hours to train a group of weak [[Viking]] villagers for a war against aliens called the Mire shortly after the Mire slaughtered all of the village's warriors and a woman called [[Ashildr]] ([[Maisie Williams]]) subsequently declared war.\n\n==Plot==\nThe [[Twelfth Doctor]] and [[Clara Oswald|Clara]] are taken to a village by some [[Viking]]s. The Doctor claims to be [[Odin]], but the villagers are not fooled. Suddenly, a figure of Odin appears in the sky, offering to take the warriors to [[Valhalla]], and a squad of warriors in armoured suits materialise, shooting the warriors with weapons that appear to disintegrate them. Clara and [[Ashildr]], a woman from the village, are also struck. The squad soon disappears.\n\n[[File:Doctor Who Experience (30855131741).jpg|thumb|left|200px|The Mire, as shown at the Doctor Who Experience]]\nClara and Ashildr find themselves on a spacecraft with the other Vikings. The men are killed and drained of their adrenaline and testosterone, while Clara and Ashildr meet Odin, the leader of the Mire species that pride themselves on their merciless conquests. Before Clara can stop her, Ashildr declares war on the Mire, and Odin grants them 24 hours to prepare. On Earth, Clara brings the Doctor up to speed. He recognises the villagers are too weak to fight, and devises a plan using Ashildr's storytelling skills and a supply of [[electric eel]]s.\n\nWhen the Mire arrive, they find the villagers celebrating. The Mire's confusion gives the Doctor time to stun them with electricity and pull one of the helmets off with an [[electromagnet]]. The Doctor modifies this and has Ashildr wear it, allowing her to envision an articulated puppet as a dragon, which is broadcast to the other Mire and scares them off. Odin vows to attack again, but the Doctor threatens to send video footage of the [[rout]] captured by Clara's phone to the universe unless they leave Earth. Odin and the Mire peacefully depart.\n\nThe village celebrates its victory until they find Ashildr died from the helmet's use. The Doctor is frustrated until he remembers why he took the form of Caecilius:{{refn|group=N|A sculptor from [[Pompeii]] whose life is saved by the [[Tenth Doctor]] in the 2008 episode \"[[The Fires of Pompeii]]\"}} to always save someone, no matter what. He \"breaks the rules\" and modifies two chips from the Mire's helmets, one which he implants in Ashildr, and the other he gives to her father for later use. The chip rapidly regenerates Ashildr's body and she regains consciousness.\n\nAs they leave, the Doctor tells Clara he fears he gave Ashildr a fate worse than death as the chip will never fail, effectively making her immortal and alone. He provided the second chip in hope she would give it to one she cares for.\n\n===Continuity===\nAfter meeting the Vikings, the Doctor produces a yo-yo in an attempt to impress them with \"magic\". A former companion, [[Leela (Doctor Who)|Leela]], believes a yo-yo is magical when the [[Fourth Doctor]] provides her one to play with (''[[The Robots of Death]]'', 1977). The [[Twelfth Doctor]] previously used one simply to test the gravity in 2014's \"[[Kill the Moon]]\",<ref name=metro>{{cite web |url= http://metro.co.uk/2015/10/18/doctor-who-did-you-spot-all-the-references-to-classic-stories-in-the-girl-who-died-5446427/|title= Doctor Who: Did you spot all the references to classic stories in The Girl Who Died?|last1= Bardock|first1= James|date= 18 October 2015|website= |publisher= |accessdate= 18 October 2015}}</ref> as did the Fourth Doctor in ''[[The Ark in Space]]'' (1975).<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2015/10/doctor-who-10-things-you-may-not-know-about-the-girl-who-died/|title='Doctor Who': 10 Things You May Not Know About 'The Girl Who Died' \u2013 Anglophenia \u2013 BBC America|work=BBC America}}</ref>\n\nThe Doctor is seen leafing through a book entitled \"2000 Year Diary\", an upgraded version of the 500 Year Diary belonging to the [[Second Doctor]] (''[[The Power of the Daleks]]'', 1966)<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/19G6tdRDTRkZy15X0mR81zh/the-girl-who-died-the-fact-file|title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who, Series 9, The Girl Who Died \u2013 The Girl Who Died: The Fact File|work=BBC}}</ref> and the 900 Year Diary of the [[Seventh Doctor]] (''[[Doctor Who (film)|Doctor Who]]'', 1996).<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe Doctor's ability to \"speak baby\" is demonstrated again in this episode. It appeared previously in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] stories \"[[A Good Man Goes to War]]\" and \"[[Closing Time (Doctor Who)|Closing Time]]\".<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nAs he is adapting a Mire helmet, the Doctor claims he is \"[[Third Doctor#.22Reverse the polarity.22|reversing the polarity of the neutron flow]]\", a phrase said many times in various ways during ''Doctor Who'', beginning with the [[Third Doctor]].<ref name=metro/>\n\n[[David Tennant]] and [[Catherine Tate]] appear in flashbacks as the [[Tenth Doctor]] and [[Donna Noble]], respectively, in scenes from \"[[The Fires of Pompeii]]\" (2008) in which [[Peter Capaldi]] also starred. A flashback from \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\" (2014), the [[Doctor Who (series 8)|eighth series]]' opening episode, also appears as the Doctor finally understands why he chose his current face.\n\nThe Doctor says Ashildr is now a \"hybrid\", echoing a prophecy related by [[Davros]] in \"[[The Magician's Apprentice (Doctor Who)|The Magician's Apprentice]]\" / \"[[The Witch's Familiar]]\" \u2013 two great warrior races, speculated to be the [[Time Lord]]s and the [[Dalek]]s, would merge to become a \"hybrid\". It now appears that, instead, it is  a merger between Vikings and the Mire.<ref name=\"Scott Collura\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/17/doctor-who-the-girl-who-died-review|title=Doctor Who: \"The Girl Who Died\" Review|author=Scott Collura|date=17 October 2015|work=IGN}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the episode, the Doctor reflects on the potential consequences of his decision to save Ashildr, and possibly making her immortal, by saying \"time will tell, it always does\". This is a statement the Seventh Doctor uses at the end of ''[[Remembrance of the Daleks]]'' (1988), referring to his decision to destroy Davros and [[Skaro]], and whether it was a 'good' decision.<ref name=metro/>\n\n===Outside references===\nOdin's face appearing in the sky to talk to his disciples directly references a scene in ''[[Monty Python and the Holy Grail]]'' in which God does the same thing.<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/>\n\nClara suggests, and the Doctor agrees, that ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]'''s [[Yakety Sax|theme song]] be used as the soundtrack for the video of Odin and the other Mire retreating from the dragon puppet. She even plays a few seconds' clip with the tune Yakety Sax's opening notes added.<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/>\n\n==Production==\n\nFilming took place at [[Margam Castle]], Castell Coch, Llanharan, and Marble Hall within [[Cardiff Town Hall]].<ref>[http://www.nla.gov.au/nla.arc-64310-20160824-0904-dwca.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/The-Nethersphere-DWCA-eNewsletter-Vol-1-No-1.pdf Page 3], April 2015, Volume 1, No 1, The Nethersphere \u2013 eNewsletter</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOdin was originally to have been played by [[Brian Blessed]], who had previously played King Yrcanos in 1986's ''[[Mindwarp]]'', and had been offered the role of the [[Second Doctor]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/aug/05/brian-blessed-turned-down-doctor-who-bbc|title= Brian Blessed: I turned down Doctor Who|author= Press Association|date= 5 August 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate= 18 October 2015|quote= \"Veteran actor says he was approached to star in the BBC show in the mid-1960s and was too busy \u2013 though he\u2019d do it now\"}}</ref> Blessed, however, was forced to pull out, and was replaced by David Schofield.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.kasterborous.com/2015/04/doctor-series-9-mystery-image-casting-update/|title= Doctor Who Series 9 Mystery Image & Casting Update|last1= Farley|first1= Connor|date= 21 April 2015|website= kasterborous.com|publisher= Kasterborous Doctor Who News|accessdate= 18 October 2015|quote= \"The role [of Odin] was originally supposed to be played by Brian Blessed\"|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150918234253/http://www.kasterborous.com/2015/04/doctor-series-9-mystery-image-casting-update/|archivedate= 18 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast and reception==\n''Doctor Who'' came second for the day with 4.63 million viewers in overnight ratings, an increase from the previous episode. Overall the episode had 6.56 million viewers, the highest figure of the series thus far, with a 28.1% share. It received an [[Appreciation Index]] score of 82.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guide.doctorwhonews.net/story.php?story=TheGirlWhoDied&episode=1 |title=Doctor Who Guide: The Girl Who Died |work=doctorwhonews.net |accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{TV ratings\n<!-- Aggregate scores -->\n| aggregate1 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Tomatometer)\n| aggregate1score = 95%<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor-who/s09/e05/|title=The Girl Who Died|date=18 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n| aggregate2 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Average Score)\n| aggregate2score = 8.33<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\"/>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev3 = [[The A.V. Club]]\n| rev3Score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/go-watch-tonights-doctor-who-right-now-please-and--227020|title=\"The Girl Who Died\" \u00b7 Doctor Who \u00b7 TV Review Go watch tonight's Doctor Who right now, please and thank you \u00b7 TV Club \u00b7 The A.V. Club|publisher=}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''Paste Magazine''\n| rev4Score = 9.6<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/10/doctor-who-review-the-girl-who-died.html|title=Doctor Who Review: \"The Girl Who Died\"|work=pastemagazine.com}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''SFX Magazine''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doctor-who-s905-girl-who-died-review/|title=Doctor Who S9.05 \u2013 \"The Girl Who Died\" review|author=Will Salmon|date=17 October 2015|work=GamesRadar+}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''TV Fanatic''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|4.5|5|score=4.3/5 stars}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2015/10/doctor-who-season-9-episode-5-review-the-girl-who-died/|title=Doctor Who|author=Alihan|work=TV Fanatic}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''IndieWire''\n| rev7Score = A++<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-doctor-who-season-9-episode-5-the-girl-who-died-keeps-a-good-thing-going-20151017|title=Review: 'Doctor Who' Season 9 Episode 5 'The Girl Who Die \u2013 Indiewire|author=Kaite Welsh|date=18 October 2015|work=Indiewire}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[IGN]]\n| rev8Score = 8.8<ref name=\"Scott Collura\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/17/doctor-who-the-girl-who-died-review|title=Doctor Who: \"The Girl Who Died\" Review|author=Scott Collura|date=17 October 2015|work=IGN}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''New York Magazine''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/10/doctor-who-recap-ripples-and-tidal-waves.html|title=Doctor Who Recap: Ripples and Tidal Waves -- Vulture|work=Vulture}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Daily Telegraph]]\n| rev10Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/doctor-who/11934817/Doctor-Who-The-Girl-Who-Died-review-recap-series-9-episode-5.html|title=Doctor Who: The Girl Who Died: Vikings and an unconventional cliffhanger|author=Catherine Gee|date=19 October 2015|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n| rev11 = [[Radio Times]]\n| rev11Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-10-17/the-girl-who-died-review-maisie-williams-and-the-vikings-conquer-doctor-who|title=Doctor Who episode 5 review: The Girl Who Died|author=Patrick Mulkern|work=RadioTimes}}</ref>\n}}\nThe episode received very positive reviews from critics, with many praising the episode's humour, the resolution with regards to the Doctor's face, and the performances of Capaldi, Coleman and Williams.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Collura|first1=Scott|title=DOCTOR WHO: \"THE GIRL WHO DIED\" REVIEW|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/10/17/doctor-who-the-girl-who-died-review|website=IGN|publisher=Scott Collura|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|last1=Wilkins|first1=Alasdair|title=Go watch tonight's Doctor Who right now, please and thank you|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/go-watch-tonights-doctor-who-right-now-please-and--227020|website=The A.V. Club|publisher=Alasdair Wilkins|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|last1=Jeffery|first1=Morgan|title=Doctor Who review: 'The Girl Who Died' is unlike anything you've seen before|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctor-who/review/a673946/doctor-who-review-the-girl-who-died-is-unlike-anything-youve-seen-before.html#~prqDvAGPGyOs85|website=Digital Spy|publisher=Morgan Jeffery|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> The episode also achieved a score of 95% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 19 reviews, with an average score of 8.1. The site's consensus reads \"With a stellar guest-star performance by Maisie Williams, \"The Girl Who Died\" sets thrillingly high stakes, while still maintaining the playful tone we've come to expect from Peter Capaldi's incarnation of Doctor Who\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor-who/s09/e05/|title=The Girl Who Died|date=19 October 2015|work=rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n\nPatrick Mulkern of ''[[Radio Times]]'' awarded the episode a perfect five star rating, claiming that \"Jamie Mathieson and Steven Moffat invest a traditional formula with a twist of unpredictability and immortality\". He further went on to say that the episode \"taps into a very traditional vein but again slyly transcends it, and achieves that holy grail of TV drama \u2013 unpredictability\", also claiming that \"everything that is meant to be funny is funny and the sad moments are sad\", while praising the episode's direction as \"impeccable\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mulkern|first1=Patrick|title=The Girl Who Died review: Maisie Williams and the Vikings conquer Doctor Who|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-10-17/the-girl-who-died-review-maisie-williams-and-the-vikings-conquer-doctor-who|website=Radio Times|publisher=Patrick Mulkern|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> Scott Collura of [[IGN]] also lavished praise onto the episode, awarding it a score of 8.8/10, deemed by the site as \"great\". He especially praised Capaldi's performance, labelling it \"big and touching\", while also enjoying \"the introduction of Maisie Williams' character\" and the episode's \"big thematic touches\". He summarised his review by stating \"Doctor Who continues its strong season with the much-anticipated arrival of Maisie Williams as \"The Girl Who Died.\" While the revelation of who her character actually is may come as something of a letdown for longtime fans, the episode itself and its bigger thematic touches more than make up for that\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> Catherine Gee of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' also enjoyed the episode, calling it \"fast paced\" and claiming that it \"set up all the right ingredients for something big next week\". She also said \"The attack and battle sequence zipped through at speed. If it felt a little rushed it didn't hugely matter, as it was clearly setting up for a bigger second half\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gee|first1=Catherine|title=Doctor Who: The Girl Who Died: 'we finally learned where the Doctor got his face'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/doctor-who/11934817/Doctor-Who-The-Girl-Who-Died-review.html|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Catherine Gee|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlasdair Wilkins of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' highly acclaimed the episode, awarding it a perfect \"A\" grade \u2013 the first of this series \u2013 and stated that \"the writing, the acting, the directing combine to create what is quite possibly the best episode yet of this Doctor's tenure\". He called the episode \"fantastically funny whenever it wants to be\", but also heavily praised the subplot of the Doctor's face, calling the reveal \"wonderfully simple\". He closed his review by labeling the episode \"a damn triumph. More than that, it's a triumph because it feels so resolutely like a ''Doctor Who'' episode\", and stated that the episode \"remembers that what motivates the Doctor's decisions are fundamentally the same emotions that we all feel, and that's what makes this such a brilliant hour of television\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Morgan Jeffery of [[Digital Spy]] also praised the episode, calling it \"unlike anything you've seen before\". He called the episode \"fast-paced, with sharp, funny dialogue and some great clowning from Peter Capaldi\" and further praising Williams' as \"nicely ethereal in the part, without ever overplaying the character's enigmatic nature\". He closed his review by saying \"while Doctor Who shouldn't be like this every week, the show's boundless variety has always been its biggest selling point, and it's refreshing to see 'The Girl Who Died' break the mould and dare to be entirely unpredictable and different\".<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nKaite Welsh of ''[[IndieWire]]'' also acclaimed the episode, awarding it an A++ grade, the highest score available. She said that the episode marked the \"fifth stellar episode in a row\", and that it represented \"the show doing historical episodes as they're meant to be done. It's like \"Fires of Pompeii\", \"Robot of Sherwood\" and classic Third Doctor adventure \"The Time Warrior\" all mixed into one\u2014literally\u2014electrifying episode\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Welsh|first1=Katie|title=Review: 'Doctor Who' Season 9 Episode 5 'The Girl Who Died' Keeps a Good Thing Going|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-doctor-who-season-9-episode-5-the-girl-who-died-keeps-a-good-thing-going-20151017|website=IndieWire|publisher=Katie Welsh|accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref> Mark Rozeman of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]]'' also responded highly positive to the episode, awarding it a score of 9.6 and saying that it \"stands up remarkably as its own story\". They closed their review by stating \"As with the best Who adventures, it explores more complexities of time travel, whilst never losing a sense of whimsy and fun. It's another home run in a season that, so far, has a pretty great batting average\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rozeman|first1=Mark|title=Doctor Who Review: \"The Girl Who Died\"|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/10/doctor-who-review-the-girl-who-died.html|website=Paste Magazine|publisher=Mark Rozeman|accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==In print==\n{{Infobox book\n|name = The Girl Who Died\n|image = \n|caption =\n|author = Jane Rollason \n|series = [[List of Doctor Who novelisations|''Doctor Who'' novelisations]]\n|release_number = \n|release_date = 25 June 2019\n|publisher = [[Pearson Education]]\n|pages = \n|isbn=  9781292206134\n}}\n\n[[Pearson Education]] published a novelisation of this episode by Jane Rollason<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bookdepository.com/Level-2-Doctor-Who-Girl-Who-Died-Jane-Rollason/9781292206134|title=Level 2: Doctor Who: The Girl Who Died : Jane Rollason : 9781292206134|first=Jane|last=Rollason|website=Book Depository}}</ref> for students of English language reading on 19 July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://online.flippingbook.com/view/922832/173/#zoom=z |title=Pearson ELT Catalogue 2018 |format=pdf |page=173}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://readers.english.com/products/detail/9781292206134|title=Level 2: Doctor Who: The Girl Who Died - Pearson Readers|website=readers.english.com|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Twelfth Doctor}}\n* {{BBCDWnew|year=2015|id=b06kv29n|title=The Girl Who Died}}\n* {{TardisIndexFile|The Girl Who Died (TV story)|\"The Girl Who Died\"}}\n\n* {{IMDb episode|4507160|The Girl Who Died}}\n\n{{Doctor Who episodes|N9}}\n{{Doctor Who episodes by Steven Moffat}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl Who Died}}\n[[Category:Twelfth Doctor episodes]]\n[[Category:2015 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Steven Moffat]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jamie Mathieson]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who pseudohistorical serials]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who stories set on Earth]]\n[[Category:Viking Age in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in the 9th century]]\n[[Category:British television episodes in multiple parts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Doctor Who episode\n| number             = 256\n| serial_name        = The Girl Who Died\n| show               = DW\n| type               = episode\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| doctor             = [[Peter Capaldi]] ([[Twelfth Doctor]])\n| companion          = [[Jenna Coleman]] ([[Clara Oswald]])\n| guests             = \n* [[Maisie Williams]] \u2013 [[Ashildr]]\n* [[David Schofield (actor)|David Schofield]] \u2013 [[Odin]]\n* [[Simon Lipkin]] \u2013 Nollarr\n* Ian Conningham \u2013 Chuckles\n* [[Tom Stourton]] \u2013 Lofty\n* Alastair Parker \u2013 Limpy\n* [[Murray McArthur]] \u2013 Hasten\n* [[Barnaby Kay]] \u2013 Heidi\n| director           = [[Edward Bazalgette|Ed Bazalgette]]\n| writer             = [[Jamie Mathieson]] <br />[[Steven Moffat]]\n| script_editor      = Nick Lambon\n| producer           = Derek Ritchie\n| executive_producer = Steven Moffat <br />Brian Minchin\n| composer           = [[Murray Gold]]\n| series             = [[Doctor Who (series 9)|Series 9]]\n| length             = 45 minutes\n| date               = {{Start date|2015|10|17|df=y}}\n| preceding          = \"[[Before the Flood (Doctor Who)|Before the Flood]]\"\n| following          = \"[[The Woman Who Lived]]\"\n}}\n\"'''The Girl Who Died'''\" is the fifth episode of the [[Doctor Who (series 9)|ninth series]] of the British [[science fiction television]] series ''[[Doctor Who]]''. It was first broadcast on [[BBC One]] on 17 October 2015. It is written by [[Jamie Mathieson]] and [[Steven Moffat]] and directed by [[Edward Bazalgette|Ed Bazalgette]].\n\nIn the episode, the alien [[Time travel in fiction|time traveller]] the [[Twelfth Doctor]] ([[Peter Capaldi]]) and his [[Companion (Doctor Who)|companion]] [[Clara Oswald|Clara]] ([[Jenna Coleman]]) have 24 hours to train a group of weak [[Viking]] villagers for a war against aliens called the Mire shortly after the Mire slaughtered all of the village's warriors and a woman called [[Ashildr]] ([[Maisie Williams]]) subsequently declared war.\n\n==Plot==\nThe [[Twelfth Doctor]] and [[Clara Oswald|Clara]] are taken to a village by some [[Viking]]s. The Doctor claims to be [[Odin]], but the villagers are not fooled. Suddenly, a figure of Odin appears in the sky, offering to take the warriors to [[Valhalla]], and a squad of warriors in armoured suits materialise, shooting the warriors with weapons that appear to disintegrate them. Clara and [[Ashildr]], a woman from the village, are also struck. The squad soon disappears.\n\n[[File:Doctor Who Experience (30855131741).jpg|thumb|left|200px|The Mire, as shown at the Doctor Who Experience]]\nClara and Ashildr find themselves on a spacecraft with the other Vikings. The men are killed and drained of their adrenaline and testosterone, while Clara and Ashildr meet Odin, the leader of the Mire species that pride themselves on their merciless conquests. Before Clara can stop her, Ashildr declares war on the Mire, and Odin grants them 24 hours to prepare. On Earth, Clara brings the Doctor up to speed. He recognises the villagers are too weak to fight, and devises a plan using Ashildr's storytelling skills and a supply of [[electric eel]]s.\n\nWhen the Mire arrive, they find the villagers celebrating. The Mire's confusion gives the Doctor time to stun them with electricity and pull one of the helmets off with an [[electromagnet]]. The Doctor modifies this and has Ashildr wear it, allowing her to envision an articulated puppet as a dragon, which is broadcast to the other Mire and scares them off. Odin vows to attack again, but the Doctor threatens to send video footage of the [[rout]] captured by Clara's phone to the universe unless they leave Earth. Odin and the Mire peacefully depart.\n\nThe village celebrates its victory until they find Ashildr died from the helmet's use. The Doctor is frustrated until he remembers why he took the form of Caecilius:{{refn|group=N|A sculptor from [[Pompeii]] whose life is saved by the [[Tenth Doctor]] in the 2008 episode \"[[The Fires of Pompeii]]\"}} to always save someone, no matter what. He \"breaks the rules\" and modifies two chips from the Mire's helmets, one which he implants in Ashildr, and the other he gives to her father for later use. The chip rapidly regenerates Ashildr's body and she regains consciousness.\n\nAs they leave, the Doctor tells Clara he fears he gave Ashildr a fate worse than death as the chip will never fail, effectively making her immortal and alone. He provided the second chip in hope she would give it to one she cares for.\n\n===Continuity===\nAfter meeting the Vikings, the Doctor produces a yo-yo in an attempt to impress them with \"magic\". A former companion, [[Leela (Doctor Who)|Leela]], believes a yo-yo is magical when the [[Fourth Doctor]] provides her one to play with (''[[The Robots of Death]]'', 1977). The [[Twelfth Doctor]] previously used one simply to test the gravity in 2014's \"[[Kill the Moon]]\",<ref name=metro>{{cite web |url= http://metro.co.uk/2015/10/18/doctor-who-did-you-spot-all-the-references-to-classic-stories-in-the-girl-who-died-5446427/|title= Doctor Who: Did you spot all the references to classic stories in The Girl Who Died?|last1= Bardock|first1= James|date= 18 October 2015|website= |publisher= |accessdate= 18 October 2015}}</ref> as did the Fourth Doctor in ''[[The Ark in Space]]'' (1975).<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2015/10/doctor-who-10-things-you-may-not-know-about-the-girl-who-died/|title='Doctor Who': 10 Things You May Not Know About 'The Girl Who Died' \u2013 Anglophenia \u2013 BBC America|work=BBC America}}</ref>\n\nThe Doctor is seen leafing through a book entitled \"2000 Year Diary\", an upgraded version of the 500 Year Diary belonging to the [[Second Doctor]] (''[[The Power of the Daleks]]'', 1966)<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/19G6tdRDTRkZy15X0mR81zh/the-girl-who-died-the-fact-file|title=BBC One \u2013 Doctor Who, Series 9, The Girl Who Died \u2013 The Girl Who Died: The Fact File|work=BBC}}</ref> and the 900 Year Diary of the [[Seventh Doctor]] (''[[Doctor Who (film)|Doctor Who]]'', 1996).<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe Doctor's ability to \"speak baby\" is demonstrated again in this episode. It appeared previously in the [[Eleventh Doctor]] stories \"[[A Good Man Goes to War]]\" and \"[[Closing Time (Doctor Who)|Closing Time]]\".<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nAs he is adapting a Mire helmet, the Doctor claims he is \"[[Third Doctor#.22Reverse the polarity.22|reversing the polarity of the neutron flow]]\", a phrase said many times in various ways during ''Doctor Who'', beginning with the [[Third Doctor]].<ref name=metro/>\n\n[[David Tennant]] and [[Catherine Tate]] appear in flashbacks as the [[Tenth Doctor]] and [[Donna Noble]], respectively, in scenes from \"[[The Fires of Pompeii]]\" (2008) in which [[Peter Capaldi]] also starred. A flashback from \"[[Deep Breath (Doctor Who)|Deep Breath]]\" (2014), the [[Doctor Who (series 8)|eighth series]]' opening episode, also appears as the Doctor finally understands why he chose his current face.\n\nThe Doctor says Ashildr is now a \"hybrid\", echoing a prophecy related by [[Davros]] in \"[[The Magician's Apprentice (Doctor Who)|The Magician's Apprentice]]\" / \"[[The Witch's Familiar]]\" \u2013 two great warrior races, speculated to be the [[Time Lord]]s and the [[Dalek]]s, would merge to become a \"hybrid\". It now appears that, instead, it is  a merger between Vikings and the Mire.<ref name=\"Scott Collura\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/17/doctor-who-the-girl-who-died-review|title=Doctor Who: \"The Girl Who Died\" Review|author=Scott Collura|date=17 October 2015|work=IGN}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the episode, the Doctor reflects on the potential consequences of his decision to save Ashildr, and possibly making her immortal, by saying \"time will tell, it always does\". This is a statement the Seventh Doctor uses at the end of ''[[Remembrance of the Daleks]]'' (1988), referring to his decision to destroy Davros and [[Skaro]], and whether it was a 'good' decision.<ref name=metro/>\n\n===Outside references===\nOdin's face appearing in the sky to talk to his disciples directly references a scene in ''[[Monty Python and the Holy Grail]]'' in which God does the same thing.<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/>\n\nClara suggests, and the Doctor agrees, that ''[[The Benny Hill Show]]'''s [[Yakety Sax|theme song]] be used as the soundtrack for the video of Odin and the other Mire retreating from the dragon puppet. She even plays a few seconds' clip with the tune Yakety Sax's opening notes added.<ref name=\"bbcamerica.com\"/>\n\n==Production==\n\nFilming took place at [[Margam Castle]], Castell Coch, Llanharan, and Marble Hall within [[Cardiff Town Hall]].<ref>[http://www.nla.gov.au/nla.arc-64310-20160824-0904-dwca.org.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/The-Nethersphere-DWCA-eNewsletter-Vol-1-No-1.pdf Page 3], April 2015, Volume 1, No 1, The Nethersphere \u2013 eNewsletter</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOdin was originally to have been played by [[Brian Blessed]], who had previously played King Yrcanos in 1986's ''[[Mindwarp]]'', and had been offered the role of the [[Second Doctor]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/aug/05/brian-blessed-turned-down-doctor-who-bbc|title= Brian Blessed: I turned down Doctor Who|author= Press Association|date= 5 August 2014|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate= 18 October 2015|quote= \"Veteran actor says he was approached to star in the BBC show in the mid-1960s and was too busy \u2013 though he\u2019d do it now\"}}</ref> Blessed, however, was forced to pull out, and was replaced by David Schofield.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.kasterborous.com/2015/04/doctor-series-9-mystery-image-casting-update/|title= Doctor Who Series 9 Mystery Image & Casting Update|last1= Farley|first1= Connor|date= 21 April 2015|website= kasterborous.com|publisher= Kasterborous Doctor Who News|accessdate= 18 October 2015|quote= \"The role [of Odin] was originally supposed to be played by Brian Blessed\"|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150918234253/http://www.kasterborous.com/2015/04/doctor-series-9-mystery-image-casting-update/|archivedate= 18 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast and reception==\n''Doctor Who'' came second for the day with 4.63 million viewers in overnight ratings, an increase from the previous episode. Overall the episode had 6.56 million viewers, the highest figure of the series thus far, with a 28.1% share. It received an [[Appreciation Index]] score of 82.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://guide.doctorwhonews.net/story.php?story=TheGirlWhoDied&episode=1 |title=Doctor Who Guide: The Girl Who Died |work=doctorwhonews.net |accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\n{{TV ratings\n<!-- Aggregate scores -->\n| aggregate1 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Tomatometer)\n| aggregate1score = 95%<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor-who/s09/e05/|title=The Girl Who Died|date=18 November 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n| aggregate2 = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] (Average Score)\n| aggregate2score = 8.33<ref name=\"rottentomatoes.com\"/>\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev3 = [[The A.V. Club]]\n| rev3Score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/go-watch-tonights-doctor-who-right-now-please-and--227020|title=\"The Girl Who Died\" \u00b7 Doctor Who \u00b7 TV Review Go watch tonight's Doctor Who right now, please and thank you \u00b7 TV Club \u00b7 The A.V. Club|publisher=}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''Paste Magazine''\n| rev4Score = 9.6<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/10/doctor-who-review-the-girl-who-died.html|title=Doctor Who Review: \"The Girl Who Died\"|work=pastemagazine.com}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''SFX Magazine''\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/doctor-who-s905-girl-who-died-review/|title=Doctor Who S9.05 \u2013 \"The Girl Who Died\" review|author=Will Salmon|date=17 October 2015|work=GamesRadar+}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''TV Fanatic''\n| rev6Score = {{rating|4.5|5|score=4.3/5 stars}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2015/10/doctor-who-season-9-episode-5-review-the-girl-who-died/|title=Doctor Who|author=Alihan|work=TV Fanatic}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''IndieWire''\n| rev7Score = A++<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-doctor-who-season-9-episode-5-the-girl-who-died-keeps-a-good-thing-going-20151017|title=Review: 'Doctor Who' Season 9 Episode 5 'The Girl Who Die \u2013 Indiewire|author=Kaite Welsh|date=18 October 2015|work=Indiewire}}</ref>\n| rev8 = [[IGN]]\n| rev8Score = 8.8<ref name=\"Scott Collura\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/10/17/doctor-who-the-girl-who-died-review|title=Doctor Who: \"The Girl Who Died\" Review|author=Scott Collura|date=17 October 2015|work=IGN}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''New York Magazine''\n| rev9Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/10/doctor-who-recap-ripples-and-tidal-waves.html|title=Doctor Who Recap: Ripples and Tidal Waves -- Vulture|work=Vulture}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Daily Telegraph]]\n| rev10Score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/doctor-who/11934817/Doctor-Who-The-Girl-Who-Died-review-recap-series-9-episode-5.html|title=Doctor Who: The Girl Who Died: Vikings and an unconventional cliffhanger|author=Catherine Gee|date=19 October 2015|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref>\n| rev11 = [[Radio Times]]\n| rev11Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-10-17/the-girl-who-died-review-maisie-williams-and-the-vikings-conquer-doctor-who|title=Doctor Who episode 5 review: The Girl Who Died|author=Patrick Mulkern|work=RadioTimes}}</ref>\n}}\nThe episode received very positive reviews from critics, with many praising the episode's humour, the resolution with regards to the Doctor's face, and the performances of Capaldi, Coleman and Williams.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last1=Collura|first1=Scott|title=DOCTOR WHO: \"THE GIRL WHO DIED\" REVIEW|url=http://uk.ign.com/articles/2015/10/17/doctor-who-the-girl-who-died-review|website=IGN|publisher=Scott Collura|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|last1=Wilkins|first1=Alasdair|title=Go watch tonight's Doctor Who right now, please and thank you|url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/go-watch-tonights-doctor-who-right-now-please-and--227020|website=The A.V. Club|publisher=Alasdair Wilkins|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|last1=Jeffery|first1=Morgan|title=Doctor Who review: 'The Girl Who Died' is unlike anything you've seen before|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/s7/doctor-who/review/a673946/doctor-who-review-the-girl-who-died-is-unlike-anything-youve-seen-before.html#~prqDvAGPGyOs85|website=Digital Spy|publisher=Morgan Jeffery|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> The episode also achieved a score of 95% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 19 reviews, with an average score of 8.1. The site's consensus reads \"With a stellar guest-star performance by Maisie Williams, \"The Girl Who Died\" sets thrillingly high stakes, while still maintaining the playful tone we've come to expect from Peter Capaldi's incarnation of Doctor Who\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/doctor-who/s09/e05/|title=The Girl Who Died|date=19 October 2015|work=rottentomatoes.com}}</ref>\n\nPatrick Mulkern of ''[[Radio Times]]'' awarded the episode a perfect five star rating, claiming that \"Jamie Mathieson and Steven Moffat invest a traditional formula with a twist of unpredictability and immortality\". He further went on to say that the episode \"taps into a very traditional vein but again slyly transcends it, and achieves that holy grail of TV drama \u2013 unpredictability\", also claiming that \"everything that is meant to be funny is funny and the sad moments are sad\", while praising the episode's direction as \"impeccable\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mulkern|first1=Patrick|title=The Girl Who Died review: Maisie Williams and the Vikings conquer Doctor Who|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-10-17/the-girl-who-died-review-maisie-williams-and-the-vikings-conquer-doctor-who|website=Radio Times|publisher=Patrick Mulkern|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref> Scott Collura of [[IGN]] also lavished praise onto the episode, awarding it a score of 8.8/10, deemed by the site as \"great\". He especially praised Capaldi's performance, labelling it \"big and touching\", while also enjoying \"the introduction of Maisie Williams' character\" and the episode's \"big thematic touches\". He summarised his review by stating \"Doctor Who continues its strong season with the much-anticipated arrival of Maisie Williams as \"The Girl Who Died.\" While the revelation of who her character actually is may come as something of a letdown for longtime fans, the episode itself and its bigger thematic touches more than make up for that\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> Catherine Gee of ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' also enjoyed the episode, calling it \"fast paced\" and claiming that it \"set up all the right ingredients for something big next week\". She also said \"The attack and battle sequence zipped through at speed. If it felt a little rushed it didn't hugely matter, as it was clearly setting up for a bigger second half\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gee|first1=Catherine|title=Doctor Who: The Girl Who Died: 'we finally learned where the Doctor got his face'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/doctor-who/11934817/Doctor-Who-The-Girl-Who-Died-review.html|website=The Telegraph|publisher=Catherine Gee|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nAlasdair Wilkins of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' highly acclaimed the episode, awarding it a perfect \"A\" grade \u2013 the first of this series \u2013 and stated that \"the writing, the acting, the directing combine to create what is quite possibly the best episode yet of this Doctor's tenure\". He called the episode \"fantastically funny whenever it wants to be\", but also heavily praised the subplot of the Doctor's face, calling the reveal \"wonderfully simple\". He closed his review by labeling the episode \"a damn triumph. More than that, it's a triumph because it feels so resolutely like a ''Doctor Who'' episode\", and stated that the episode \"remembers that what motivates the Doctor's decisions are fundamentally the same emotions that we all feel, and that's what makes this such a brilliant hour of television\".<ref name=\"auto1\"/> Morgan Jeffery of [[Digital Spy]] also praised the episode, calling it \"unlike anything you've seen before\". He called the episode \"fast-paced, with sharp, funny dialogue and some great clowning from Peter Capaldi\" and further praising Williams' as \"nicely ethereal in the part, without ever overplaying the character's enigmatic nature\". He closed his review by saying \"while Doctor Who shouldn't be like this every week, the show's boundless variety has always been its biggest selling point, and it's refreshing to see 'The Girl Who Died' break the mould and dare to be entirely unpredictable and different\".<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nKaite Welsh of ''[[IndieWire]]'' also acclaimed the episode, awarding it an A++ grade, the highest score available. She said that the episode marked the \"fifth stellar episode in a row\", and that it represented \"the show doing historical episodes as they're meant to be done. It's like \"Fires of Pompeii\", \"Robot of Sherwood\" and classic Third Doctor adventure \"The Time Warrior\" all mixed into one\u2014literally\u2014electrifying episode\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Welsh|first1=Katie|title=Review: 'Doctor Who' Season 9 Episode 5 'The Girl Who Died' Keeps a Good Thing Going|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/review-doctor-who-season-9-episode-5-the-girl-who-died-keeps-a-good-thing-going-20151017|website=IndieWire|publisher=Katie Welsh|accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref> Mark Rozeman of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste Magazine]]'' also responded highly positive to the episode, awarding it a score of 9.6 and saying that it \"stands up remarkably as its own story\". They closed their review by stating \"As with the best Who adventures, it explores more complexities of time travel, whilst never losing a sense of whimsy and fun. It's another home run in a season that, so far, has a pretty great batting average\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rozeman|first1=Mark|title=Doctor Who Review: \"The Girl Who Died\"|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/10/doctor-who-review-the-girl-who-died.html|website=Paste Magazine|publisher=Mark Rozeman|accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==In print==\n{{Infobox book\n|name = The Girl Who Died\n|image = \n|caption =\n|author = Jane Rollason \n|series = [[List of Doctor Who novelisations|''Doctor Who'' novelisations]]\n|release_number = \n|release_date = 25 June 2019\n|publisher = [[Pearson Education]]\n|pages = \n|isbn=  9781292206134\n}}\n\n[[Pearson Education]] published a novelisation of this episode by Jane Rollason<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bookdepository.com/Level-2-Doctor-Who-Girl-Who-Died-Jane-Rollason/9781292206134|title=Level 2: Doctor Who: The Girl Who Died : Jane Rollason : 9781292206134|first=Jane|last=Rollason|website=Book Depository}}</ref> for students of English language reading on 19 July 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://online.flippingbook.com/view/922832/173/#zoom=z |title=Pearson ELT Catalogue 2018 |format=pdf |page=173}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://readers.english.com/products/detail/9781292206134|title=Level 2: Doctor Who: The Girl Who Died - Pearson Readers|website=readers.english.com|accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Twelfth Doctor}}\n* {{BBCDWnew|year=2015|id=b06kv29n|title=The Girl Who Died}}\n* {{TardisIndexFile|The Girl Who Died (TV story)|\"The Girl Who Died\"}}\n\n* {{IMDb episode|4507160|The Girl Who Died}}\n\n{{Doctor Who episodes|N9}}\n{{Doctor Who episodes by Steven Moffat}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Girl Who Died}}\n[[Category:Twelfth Doctor episodes]]\n[[Category:2015 British television episodes]]\n[[Category:Television episodes written by Steven Moffat]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Jamie Mathieson]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who pseudohistorical serials]]\n[[Category:Doctor Who stories set on Earth]]\n[[Category:Viking Age in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in the 9th century]]\n[[Category:British television episodes in multiple parts]]\n", "name_user": "LegoKeoni", "label": "safe", "comment": "Amended running time", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Girl_Who_Died"}
{"title_page": "Lilith Fair", "text_new": "{{Short description|Defunct American female-centric concert tour/music festival}}\n[[File:jp49819980922-lilithfair.jpg|thumb|350px|right|The main stage, September 22, 1998, [[Tweeter Center Boston|Tweeter Center]], [[Mansfield, Massachusetts]].]]\n'''Lilith Fair''' was a [[concert tour]] and travelling [[music festival]], founded by Canadian musician [[Sarah McLachlan]], [[Nettwerk Music Group]]'s [[Dan Fraser]] and [[Terry McBride (CEO)|Terry McBride]], and New York talent agent Marty Diamond. It took place during the summers of 1997 to 1999, and was revived in the summer of 2010. It consisted solely of female solo artists and female-led bands. In its initial three years, Lilith Fair raised over $10M for charity.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=128588089 |title=With Sales Lagging, Lilith Fair Faces Question Of Relevance |last=Pellegrinelli |first=Lara |date=19 July 2010 |website=NPR |access-date=30 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1996, Canadian [[Sarah McLachlan]] became frustrated with concert promoters and radio stations that refused to feature two female musicians in a row.<ref name=\"cnn072898\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Music/9807/28/lilith.fair/ | title=Lilith Fair: Lovely, lively and long overdue | author=Donna Freydkin | publisher=CNN | date=1998-07-28 | accessdate=2008-07-04}}</ref> Bucking conventional industry wisdom, she booked a successful tour for herself and [[Paula Cole]]. At least one of their appearances together\u2014in McLachlan's hometown of [[Vancouver]], on September 14, 1996\u2014went by the name \"Lilith Fair\" and included performances by McLachlan, Cole, [[Lisa Loeb]] and [[Michelle McAdorey]], formerly of [[Crash Vegas]].\n\nThe next year, McLachlan founded the Lilith Fair tour, taking ''Lilith'' from the Jewish lore that [[Lilith]] was the first woman, who refused to be subservient to [[Adam]].\n\nIn 1997, Lilith Fair garnered a $16 million gross, making it the top-grossing of any touring festival.<ref name=\"cnn072898\"/>  Among all concert tours for that year, it was the 16th highest grossing.<ref name=\"cnn072898\"/> McLachlan followed this success with two more rounds in 1998 and 1999.\n\nIn 2010, Lilith Fair staged a revival with mixed results, as several dates were canceled and many performers backed out of scheduled performances.\n\nIn March 2011, co-founder Sarah McLachlan declared that the Lilith concept was no longer being considered for future shows, due to changing audience views and expectations.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/music/sarah-mclachlan-says-lilith-fair-is-over/article569791/ | title=Sarah McLachlan says Lilith Fair is over | author=MARSHA LEDERMAN | publisher=Toronto Globe and Mail | date=2011-03-08 | accessdate=2011-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Performers==\n\n===1997===\nThe artists appearing at Lilith Fair varied by date (with McLachlan and Suzanne Vega the only artists to play all dates). Appearances were organized into three stages. Almost all Village Stage artists performed only one or two dates. Many of them won slots on the bill in a series of local talent searches in their home cities.\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n;Main stage artists\n*[[Sarah McLachlan]]\n*[[Sheryl Crow]]\n*[[Tracy Chapman]]\n*[[Jewel (singer)|Jewel]]\n*[[Paula Cole]]\n*[[Suzanne Vega]]\n*[[Mary Chapin Carpenter]]\n*[[Fiona Apple]]\n*[[Joan Osborne]]\n*[[The Cardigans]]\n*[[Emmylou Harris]]\n*[[Lisa Loeb]]\n*[[Indigo Girls]]\n*[[Shawn Colvin]]\n*[[Meredith Brooks]]\n*[[Tracy Bonham]]\n*[[India Arie]]\n*[[Natalie Merchant]]\n{{Col-break}}\n\n;Second stage artists\n*Jenny Labow\n*[[Cassandra Wilson]]\n*[[Suz Andreasen]]\n*[[Leah Andreone]]\n*[[Kim Bingham|Mudgirl]]\n*[[Wild Colonials]]\n*[[September '67]]\n*[[Tara MacLean]]\n*[[Victoria Williams]]\n*[[Autour de Lucie]]\n*[[Holly Cole]]\n*[[Juliana Hatfield]]\n*Once Blue\n*[[Susanna Hoffs]]\n*[[Abra Moore]]\n*[[Kelly Willis]]\n*[[Katell Keineg]]\n*[[Mary Black]]\n*[[Davina (R&B singer)|Davina]]\n*[[Madeleine Peyroux]]\n*[[Patty Griffin]]\n*[[Yungchen Lhamo]]\n*[[Dayna Manning]]\n*[[Lhasa de Sela]]\n*[[Wild Strawberries (band)|Wild Strawberries]]\n*[[Dar Williams]]\n*[[Mary Jane Lamond]]\n*[[Morcheeba]]\n*[[K's Choice]]\n{{Col-break}}\n\n;Village Stage artists\n*[[Fleming and John]]\n*[[Dido (singer)|Dido]]\n*[[Pat Benatar]]\n*[[Kinnie Starr]]\n*[[Lauren Hoffman]]\n*Kim Fox\n*[[Garrison Starr]]\n*[[Lori Carson]]\n*Joy Askew\n*[[Jill Sobule]]\n*[[Alana Davis]]\n*[[Beth Orton]]\n*[[Michelle Malone]]\n*[[Holly McNarland]]\n*Elise Knoll\n*Lovechild\n*[[Dayna Manning]]\n*Catherine Kidd\n*[[Suzie Ungerleider|Oh Suzanna]]\n*[[Camille (singer)|Camille]]\n*[[Alisha's Attic]]\n*Gena and Sum Girl\n*Sensual World\n{{col-end}}\n\n;Dates\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| City\n! style=\"width:90px;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:200px;\"| Venue\n|-\n| July 5\n| [[George, Washington|George]]\n| rowspan=\"19\"|United States\n| [[The Gorge Amphitheatre|The Gorge]]\n|-\n| July 6\n| [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]]\n| [[L. B. Day Amphitheatre]]\n|-\n| July 8\n| [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]]\n| [[Shoreline Amphitheatre]]\n|-\n| July 9\n| [[Irvine, California|Irvine]]\n| [[Irvine Meadows Amphitheatre]]\n|-\n| July 10\n| [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n| [[Desert Sky Pavilion]]\n|-\n| July 12\n| [[Winter Park, Colorado|Winter Park]]\n| Winter Park Music Festival\n|-\n| July 14\n| [[Bonner Springs, Kansas|Bonner Springs]]\n| [[Sandstone Amphitheatre]]\n|-\n| July 15\n| [[Maryland Heights, Missouri|Maryland Heights]]\n| [[Riverport Amphitheatre]]\n|-\n| July 17\n| [[Cuyahoga Falls, Ohio|Cuyahoga Falls]]\n| [[Blossom Music Center]]\n|-\n| July 18\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Clarkston, Michigan|Clarkston]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Pine Knob Music Theatre]]\n|-\n| July 19\n|-\n| July 20\n| [[Canandaigua (city), New York|Canandaigua]]\n| [[Finger Lakes P.A.C.]]\n|-\n| July 22\n| [[Mansfield, Massachusetts|Mansfield]]\n| [[Great Woods Center]]\n|-\n| July 24\n| [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford]]\n| [[Meadows Music Theatre]]\n|-\n| July 25\n| [[Wantagh, New York|Wantagh]]\n| [[Jones Beach State Park|Jones Beach]]\n|-\n| July 26\n| [[Holmdel Township, New Jersey|Holmdel]]\n| [[PNC Bank Arts Center]]\n|-\n| July 27\n| [[Camden, New Jersey|Camden]]\n| [[Blockbuster-Sony E-Centre]]\n|-\n| July 29\n| [[Columbia, Maryland|Columbia]]\n| [[Merriweather Post Pavilion]]\n|-\n| July 30\n| [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]]\n| [[Walnut Creek Pavilion]]\n|}\n\n{{Col-break}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| City\n! style=\"width:90px;\"| Country\n! style=\"width:200px;\"| Venue\n|-\n| July 31\n| [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]]\n|rowspan=\"11\"|United States\n| [[Blockbuster Pavilion Charlotte|Blockbuster Pavilion]]\n|-\n| August 1\n| [[Atlanta]]\n| [[Coca-Cola Lakewood]]\n|-\n| August 3\n| [[The Woodlands, Texas|The Woodlands]]\n| [[Cynthia Woods Mitchell Pavilion|Woodlands]]\n|-\n| August 4\n| [[Dallas]]\n| [[Starplex Amphitheatre|Starplex]]\n|-\n| August 6\n| [[Antioch, Tennessee|Antioch]]\n| [[Starwood Amphitheatre]]\n|-\n| August 7\n| [[Cincinnati]]\n| [[Riverbend Music Center]]\n|-\n| August 8\n| [[Noblesville, Indiana|Noblesville]]\n| [[Deer Creek Music Center]]\n|-\n| August 9\n| [[Tinley Park, Illinois|Tinley Park]]\n| [[New World Music Theater]]\n|-\n| August 10\n| [[Columbus, Ohio|Columbus]]\n| [[Polaris Amphitheater]]\n|-\n| August 12\n| [[Burgettstown, Pennsylvania|Burgettstown]]\n| [[Star Lake Amphitheater|Star Lake]]\n|-\n| August 13\n| [[Scranton, Pennsylvania|Scranton]]\n| [[Toyota Pavilion at Montage Mountain|Montage Mountain]]\n|-\n| August 15\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Toronto]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Canada\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Molson Amphitheatre]]\n|-\n| August 16\n|-\n| August 17\n| [[Montreal]]